abstract_ts:
Let $\Omega\subset\mathbb{R}^n$, $n\ge 2$, be a bounded connected $C^2$ domain. For any unit vector $
u\in\mathbb{R}^n$, let $T_{\lambda}^{
u}=\{x\in\mathbb{R}^n:x\cdot
u=\lambda\}$, $\Sigma_{\lambda}^{
u}=\{x\in\Omega:x\cdot
u<\lambda\}$ and $x^{\ast}=x-2(x\cdot
u-\lambda)
u$ be the reflection of a point $x\in\mathbb{R}^n$ about the plane $T_{\lambda}^{
u}$. Let $\widetilde{\Sigma}_{\lambda}^{
u}=\{x\in\Omega:x^{\ast}\in\Sigma_{\lambda}^{
u}\}$ and $u\in C^2(\overline{\Omega})$. Suppose for any unit vector $
u\in\mathbb{R}^n$, there exists a constant $\lambda_{
u}\in\mathbb{R}$ such that $\Omega$ is symmetric about the plane $T_{\lambda_{
u}}^{
u}$ and $u$ is symmetric about the plane $T_{\lambda_{
u}}^{
u}$ and satisfies (i)$\, rac{\partial u}{\partial
u}(x)>0\quad orall x\in \Sigma_{\lambda_{
u}}^{
u}$ and (ii)$\, rac{\partial u}{\partial
u}(x)<0\quad orall x\in \widetilde{\Sigma}_{\lambda_{
u}}^{
u}$. We will give a simple proof that $u$ is radially symmetric about some point $x_0\in\Omega$ and $\Omega$ is a ball with center at $x_0$. Similar result holds for the domain $\mathbb{R}^n$ and function $u\in C^2(\mathbb{R}^n)$ satisfying similar monotonicity and symmetry conditions. We also extend this result under weaker hypothesis on the function $u$.
